<h1><b>Tobacco Policy Project/State Legislated Actions on Tobacco Issues (SLATI)</b></h1>
<h3>The Latest</h3>
<ul type="disc">
    <li>On September 14, the American Lung Association released data for all 50 states and DC showing the economic benefits states receive by covering tobacco cessation treatments.  For more information, click <a href="http://www.lungusa.org/stop-smoking/tobacco-control-advocacy/reports-resources/cessation-economic-benefits" target="_blank">here</a>.</li>
    <li>On  July 1, cigarette tax increases took effect in five states &ndash; <a href="/statedetail.php?id=11">Hawaii</a>, <a href="/statedetail.php?id=31">New Mexico</a>,  <a href="/statedetail.php?id=32">New York</a>, <a href="/statedetail.php?id=40">South Carolina</a> and <a href="/statedetail.php?id=44">Utah</a>. New York now has the highest cigarette  tax in the country at $4.35 per pack and Missouri  has the lowest at 17 cents. For more information on tobacco taxes, click <a href="/tobacco_taxes.php">here</a>.</li>
    <li>On July 1 in <a href="/statedetail.php?id=16">Kansas</a> and July 5 in <a href="/statedetail.php?id=49">Wisconsin</a>, laws prohibiting smoking  in almost all public places and workplaces, including restaurants and bars took  effect.&nbsp; For more information on  smokefree laws and policies, click <a href="/smokefree_laws.php">here</a>.</li>
</ul>
<p>Welcome  to the American Lung Association&rsquo;s Tobacco Policy Project/State Legislated  Actions on Tobacco Issues (SLATI) website.&nbsp; This website is home to the  online version of SLATI, which tracks state tobacco control laws, such as  restrictions on smoking in public places and workplaces and tobacco taxes, on  an ongoing basis. It is the only comprehensive and up-to-date summary of  tobacco control laws in all 50 states and the District of Columbia.</p>
